# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: incorporation-by-reference
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] Also, in the case of legacies when the funds or assets out of which they are payable are not sufficient to pay them in full, the legacies abate in proportion, unless there is a priority given specially to any particular legacy.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] Annuities are also subject to the same rule as general legacies.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] Demonstrative Devises—*i.e.*, cash gifts from a specific account, stocks, bonds, securities, etc.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] Specific Devises—*i.e.*, specified items of personal property, real property, etc.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] Non-probate property—*i.e.*, life insurance policies—do not abate.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] A **specific devise**, is a specific gift in a will to a specific person other than an amount of money.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] For example, if James's will states that he is leaving his $500,000 yacht to his brother Mike, the yacht would be a specific devise.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] A **general devise**, is a monetary gift to a specific person to be satisfied out of the overall estate.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] For example, if James's will states that he is leaving $500,000 to his son Sam then the money would be a general devise.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] A **demonstrative devise**, is money given from a particular account.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] A **residual devise** is one left to a devisee after all specific and general devices have been made.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/abatement-of-debts-and-legacies] For example, James's will might say: "I give all the rest, residue and remainder of my estate to my daughter Lilly." Lilly would be the residual devisee and entitled to James's residuary estate.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/acts-of-independent-significance] The doctrine of **acts of independent significance** at common law permits a testator to effectively change the disposition of his property without changing a will, if acts or events changing the disposition have some significance beyond avoiding the requirements of the will.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/acts-of-independent-significance] The testator devises a general type of property, and then changes the specific items of property within that category.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/acts-of-independent-significance] For example, Joey writes in his will, "I leave my car to Rachel".
[src:incorporation-by-reference/acts-of-independent-significance] Joey drives a 1974 AMC Gremlin at the time of the testamentary instrument, but later sells the Gremlin and purchases a 2016 Rolls-Royce Phantom Drophead Coupé with suicide doors and teak paneling.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/acts-of-independent-significance] Because Joey bought a new car to get a more comfortable ride, rather than to change a will without going through the testamentary formalities, the gift to Rachel remains enforceable.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/acts-of-independent-significance] A will may dispose of property by reference to acts and events that have significance apart from their effect upon the dispositions made by the will, whether they occur before or after the execution of the will or before or after the testator's death.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/acts-of-independent-significance] The execution or revocation of another individual's will is such an event.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption-by-satisfaction] In the United States, state law determines which lifetime gifts are treated as gifts in satisfaction of a bequest.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption-by-satisfaction] Courts may presume that gifts of money from a parent to a child after the execution of the parent's will are gifts in satisfaction of the child's legacy under the will, even without a written indication of intent to satisfy the provision under the will.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption-by-satisfaction] Courts are reluctant to apply the doctrine to certain kinds of legacies, for example, devises of specific real estate or bequests of personal property.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption-by-satisfaction] These specific legacies are viewed by courts as unique and not able to be replaced with a lifetime gift of money or other property.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption-by-satisfaction] When the probate court determines that the doctrine applies to a lifetime gift made to a will beneficiary, the amount beneficiary's gift under the will is reduced by the amount the beneficiary has already received.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption-by-satisfaction] For example, if the will bequeaths $5,000 to a beneficiary, but the beneficiary received a lifetime gift of $4,000 from testator that was intended to partially satisfy the gift under the will, the beneficiary will receive only $1,000 under the will.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption-by-satisfaction] If the will provides that the beneficiary receives a percentage of the testator's estate, the court may engage in a hotchpot calculation to determine the amount, if any, that the beneficiary should receive under the will.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption-by-satisfaction] If the value of the lifetime gift received is greater than the beneficiary's calculated share under the will, the beneficiary receives nothing under the will, but does not return any of the lifetime gifts.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] General bequests or **general gifts** - gifts of cash amounts - are never adeemed.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] If the cash in the testator's estate is not sufficient to satisfy the gift, then other assets in the residuary estate will need to be sold to raise the necessary cash.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] Some property lies in a "gray" area, in which the testator's specific intent must be determined.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] Such a gift is deemed to be a demonstrative gift.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] Such demonstrative gifts are deemed to be a hybrid of both specific and general gifts.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] If one were to bequeath "500 shares of stock," most states would deem that to be a demonstrative gift.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] The resultant gift to the heir receiving "500 shares," would be the date of death value of 500 shares of that particular stock.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] Ademption may be waived if the property leaves the estate after the testator has been declared incompetent.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] Furthermore, in some cases the beneficiary will be entitled to the proceeds from the sale of property, or to the insurance payout for property that is lost or destroyed.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] To avoid confusion as to what may or may not be adeemed, sometimes the phrase "if owned by me at my death" is placed into the articles of a will in which property is being bequeathed.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] As for the sale of land under an executory contract, traditional case law agrees that ademption occurs upon the death of the testator and that the proceeds of sale, when the closing occurs, should not pass to the specific devisee of the property.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] However, the more modern view and the Uniform Probate Code, which has been adopted by some U.S. jurisdictions, disagrees.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] These jurisdictions find that when property subject to specific devise is placed under contract of sale before the decedent's death, the proceeds of the sale will pass to the specific devisee.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] Many U.S. jurisdictions have ameliorated the effects of the common law doctrine by statute.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] In Wisconsin, state law (854.08) attempts to abolish the common law doctrine of ademption by extinction, by, for example, awarding beneficiaries the balance of the purchase price of the item sold (subject to some limitations).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/ademption] In Virginia, ademption occurs with respect to most forms of property, but if the property at issue is stock certificates, then the buyout of the issuer of the stock by another company, and the swapping of the stocks for a new issue by that company, will not adeem the gift of stock.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] In common-law jurisdictions, **administration** of an estate on death arises if the deceased is legally intestate, meaning they did not leave a will, or some assets are not disposed of by their will.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] Where a person dies leaving a will appointing an executor, and that executor validly disposes of the property of the deceased within England and Wales, then the estate will go to probate.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] However, if no will is left, or the will is invalid or incomplete in some way, then administrators must be appointed.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] They perform a similar role to the executor of a will but, where there are no instructions in a will, the administrators must distribute the estate of the deceased according to the rules laid down by statute and the common trust.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] Certain property falls outside the estate for administration purposes, the most common example probably being houses jointly owned that pass by survivorship on the first death of a couple into the sole name of the survivor.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] Other examples include discretionary death benefits from pension funds, accounts with certain financial institutions subject to a nomination and the proceeds of life insurance policies which have been written into trust.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] Trust property will also frequently fall outside the estate but will depend on the terms of the trust.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] The estate settlement process typically takes between 12 and 18 months, depending on the estate's size, complexity and if there are existing disputes.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] The court does this by granting letters of administration to the person so entitled.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] Grants of administration may be either general (where the deceased has died intestate) or limited.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] Under the rules for distribution of estates without a will (the Intestacy Rules), where a child under 18 would inherit or a life interest would arise, the Court or District Probate Registry normally appoints a minimum of two administrators.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] On some estates, even under an intestate, it is not clear who are the next-of-kin, and probate research may be required to find the entitled beneficiaries.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] An administrator (sometimes known as the administratrix, if female) acts as the personal representative of the deceased in relation to land and other property in the UK.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] Consequently, when the estate under administration consists wholly or mainly of land, the court will grant administration to the heir to the exclusion of the next of kin.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] In the absence of any heir or next of kin, the Crown has the right to property (other than land) as *bona vacantia*, and to the land by virtue of the historic land rights of the Crown (and the Duchy of Cornwall and Duchy of Lancaster in their respective areas).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] If a creditor claims and obtains a Grant of Administration, the court compels him or her to enter into a bond with two or more sureties that he or she will not prefer his or her debt to those of other creditors.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administration-probate-law] In the first case the principle of *administration cum testamento* is followed, in the second that of general grants in the selection of the person to whom letters are granted.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Administrative law deals with the decision-making of administrative units of government that are part of the executive branch in such areas as international trade, manufacturing, the environment, taxation, broadcasting, immigration, and transport.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Administrative law expanded greatly during the 20th century, as legislative bodies worldwide created more government agencies to regulate the social, economic and political spheres of human interaction.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Civil law countries often have specialized administrative courts that review these decisions.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In Brazil, administrative cases are typically heard either by the Federal Courts (in matters concerning the Federal Union) or by the Public Treasury divisions of State Courts (in matters concerning the States).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In 1998 a constitutional reform led by the government of President Fernando Henrique Cardoso introduced regulatory agencies as a part of the executive branch.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Since 1988, Brazilian administrative law has been strongly influenced by the judicial interpretations of the constitutional principles of public administration (Art.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] 37 of the Federal Constitution): legality, impersonality, publicity of administrative acts, morality and efficiency.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In Chile, the President of the Republic exercises the administrative function, in collaboration with several ministries or other authorities with *ministerial rank*.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Each ministry has one or more under-secretaries that act through public service to meet public needs.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] There is no single specialized court to deal with actions against the administrative entities, but there are several specialized courts and procedures of review.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Administrative law in China was virtually non-existent before the economic reform era initiated by Deng Xiaoping.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Since the 1980s China has constructed a new legal framework for administrative law, establishing control mechanisms for overseeing the bureaucracy, and disciplinary committees for the Chinese Communist Party.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In 1989, China established its Administrative Litigation Law, which provides an avenue for people to challenge government action.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In 2014, it was amended to lower the burdens on those challenging administrative actions.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In 1990, the Administrative Supervision Regulations (行政检查条例) and the Administrative Reconsideration Regulations (行政复议条例) were passed.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The 1993 State Civil Servant Provisional Regulations (国家公务员暂行条例) changed the way government officials were selected and promoted, requiring that they pass exams and yearly appraisals, and introducing a rotation system.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The three regulations have been amended and upgraded into laws.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In 1994, the State Compensation Law (国家赔偿法) was passed, followed by the Administrative Penalties Law (行政处罚法) in 1996.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Administrative Compulsory Law was enforced in 2012.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The General Administrative Procedure Law is underway.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In France, there is a dual jurisdictional system with the judiciary branch responsible for civil law and criminal law, and the administrative branch having jurisdiction when a government institution is involved.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Most claims against the national or local governments as well as claims against private bodies providing public services are handled by administrative courts, which use the *Conseil d'État* (Council of State) as a court of last resort for both ordinary and special courts.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The main administrative courts are the *tribunaux administratifs* and appeal courts are the *cours administratives d'appel*.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Special administrative courts include the National Court of Asylum Right as well as military, medical and judicial disciplinary bodies.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The French body of administrative law is called "*droit administratif*".
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] French administrative law, the basis of continental administrative law, has had a strong influence on administrative laws in several other countries such as Belgium, Greece, Turkey and Tunisia.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In Germany, administrative law (German: *Verwaltungsrecht*) includes all law that specifically governs the legal relationships between public authorities and private persons, and that is not more precisely described as constitutional law.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] It sets out the tasks, aims and powers, as well as the organization and procedure, for all public authorities (German: *Behörden*).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] As a field of legal study, administrative law has been differentiated from other branches of public law since the late 19th century in Germany; the precise delimitations of "administration" as a concept, however, are in contention.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Administrative law defines all aspects of public administration in the modern German state, whose legal culture emphasizes private persons' subjective rights (also, pursuant to art.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] 19IV of the current German Constitution of 1949, such rights must be fully justiciable).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The final say on the interpretation of the law lies with the courts of administrative jurisdiction (German: *Verwaltungsgerichte*), and the law usually permits close judicial scrutiny of public authorities' exercise of discretion.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] German legal scholarship does not have an agreed-upon definition for public administration.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In one sense, administration – more precisely, everything that is subject to administrative law – is conceptualized as being all state activity of a certain type (material definition of public administration).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] There is some danger of circular reasoning, since the formal categorization of the organizational unit may, in turn, derive from some material conception of its function.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] This discussion is of seen as being of particular importance when considering the role of administrative law in maintaining the division of government powers.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] For this purpose, a traditional approach tries negatively to define administration by subtracting those operations of the state which cannot be called administration, namely law-making and adjudication.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Using this negative definition, though, requires law-making and adjudication to be defined first, and leaves some activities that are a poor fit for the term "administration", such as the cabinet government's political leadership decisions, within the bounds of the definition.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Positive definitions abound, but none has won out over the others, or been entirely convincing to scholars of German administrative law.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] 'special administrative law') – e.g. police law, urban planning law, or local government law.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The is not a full codification of the generally applicable ground rules of German administrative law, since it mostly only determines the procedure to be followed by public authorities in the fulfillment of their tasks, rather than mandating the substance of public administration.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The VwVfG is a federal law that only applies to administration carried out by the German federal authorities.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] All 16 German *Länder* have, however, enacted a Law on Administrative Procedure of their own that is nearly word-for-word identical with the federal VwVfG.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The standard form of administrative is the *Verwaltungsakt* (administrative ordinance).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Pursuant to VwVfG § 35, an administrative ordinance exists where: a public authority (1) issues any decree, decision, or other official measure (2), in a matter of public law (3), with immediate legal effects outside the administration (4), to put in place a rule for an individual case (5).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The law governing the adjudication of questions of administrative law before the courts of general administrative jurisdiction (German: *Verwaltungsgerichte*) is the Code on Administrative Courts (German: *Verwaltungsgerichtsordnung*, abbreviated VwGO), which was enacted in 1960.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The VwGO also does not apply to the courts of special administrative jurisdiction over tax disputes (German: *Finanzgerichte*) or over social benefits disputes (German: *Sozialgerichte*).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In Italy, administrative law is known as *Diritto amministrativo*, a branch of public law whose rules govern the organization of the public administration and the activities of the pursuit of the public interest of the public administration and the relationship between this and the citizens.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Its genesis is related to the principle of division of powers of the State.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The administrative power, originally called "executive", is to organize resources and people whose function is devolved to achieve the public interest objectives as defined by the law.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In the Netherlands administrative law provisions are usually contained in the various laws about public services and regulations.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] There is however also a single General Administrative Law Act (*Algemene wet bestuursrecht* or Awb), which is a rather good sample of procedural laws in Europe.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] It applies both to the making of administrative decisions and the judicial review of these decisions in courts.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Another act about judicial procedures in general is the *Algemene termijnenwet* (General time provisions act), with general provisions about time schedules in procedures.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] On the basis of the Awb, citizens can oppose a decision (*besluit*) made by an administrative agency (*bestuursorgaan*) within the administration and apply for judicial review in courts if unsuccessful.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Before going to court, citizens must usually first object to the decision with the administrative body that made it.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] This procedure allows for the administrative body to correct possible mistakes themselves and is used to filter cases before going to court.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Sometimes, instead of *bezwaar*, a different system is used called *administratief beroep* (administrative appeal).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The difference with *bezwaar* is that *administratief beroep* is filed with a different administrative body, usually a higher ranking one, than the administrative body that made the primary decision.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] *Administratief beroep* is available only if the law on which the primary decision is based specifically provides for it.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] An example involves objecting to a traffic ticket with the district attorney (*officier van justitie*), after which the decision can be appealed in court.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Unlike France or Germany, there are no special administrative courts of first instance in the Netherlands, but regular courts have an administrative "chamber" which specializes in administrative appeals.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In Sweden, there is a system of administrative courts that considers only administrative law cases and is completely separate from the system of general courts.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] This system has three tiers, with 12 county administrative courts (*förvaltningsrätt*) as the first tier, four administrative courts of appeal (*kammarrätt*) as the second tier, and the Supreme Administrative Court of Sweden (*Högsta Förvaltningsdomstolen*) as the third tier.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Migration cases are handled in a two-tier system, effectively within the system of general administrative courts.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Three of the administrative courts serve as migration courts (*migrationsdomstol*) with the Administrative Court of Appeal in Stockholm serving as the Migration Court of Appeal (*Migrationsöverdomstolen*), from which appeals may go to the *Högsta Förvaltningsdomstolen*.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In Taiwan the recently enacted *Constitutional Procedure Act* (憲法訴訟法) in 2019 (former *Constitutional Interpretation Procedure Act, 1993*), the **Justices of the Constitutional Court** of Judicial Yuan of Taiwan is in charge of judicial interpretation.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] As of 2019, this council has made 757 interpretations.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In Turkey, the lawsuits against the acts and actions of the national or local governments and public bodies are handled by administrative courts which are the main administrative courts.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The decisions of the administrative courts are checked by the Regional Administrative Courts and Council of State.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Council of State as a court of last resort is exactly similar to Conseil d'État in France.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Administrative law in Ukraine is a homogeneous legal substance isolated in a system of jurisprudence characterized as: (1) a branch of law; (2) a science; (3) a discipline.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Generally speaking, most countries that follow the principles of common law have developed procedures for judicial review that limit the reviewability of decisions made by administrative law bodies.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Often these procedures are coupled with legislation or other common law doctrines that establish standards for proper rulemaking.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Administrative law may also apply to the review of decisions of so-called semi-public bodies, such as non-profit corporations, disciplinary boards, and other decision-making bodies that affect the legal rights of members of a particular group or entity.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] While administrative decision-making bodies are often controlled by larger governmental units, their decisions could be reviewed by a court of general jurisdiction under some principle of judicial review based upon due process (United States) or fundamental justice (Canada).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Judicial review of administrative decisions is different from an administrative appeal.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] When sitting in review of a decision, the Court will only look at the method in which the decision was arrived at, whereas in an administrative appeal, the correctness of the decision itself will be examined, usually by a higher body in the agency.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] This difference is vital in appreciating administrative law in common law countries.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The scope of judicial review may be limited to certain questions of fairness, or whether the administrative action is *ultra vires*.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Administrative Procedure Act and New York State law).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Administrative law, as laid down by the Supreme Court of India, has also recognized two more grounds of judicial review which were recognized but not applied by English Courts, namely legitimate expectation and proportionality.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The powers to review administrative decisions are usually established by statute but were originally developed from the royal prerogative writs of English law, such as the writ of mandamus and the writ of certiorari.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In certain common law jurisdictions, such as India or Pakistan, the power to pass such writs is a Constitutionally guaranteed power.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] This power is seen as fundamental to the power of judicial review and an aspect of the independent judiciary.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In the United States, many government agencies are organized under the executive branch of government, although a few are part of the judicial or legislative branches.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In the federal government, the executive branch, led by the president, controls the federal executive departments, which are led by secretaries who are members of the United States Cabinet.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The many independent agencies of the United States government created by statutes enacted by Congress exist outside of the federal executive departments but are still part of the executive branch.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Congress has also created some special judicial bodies known as Article I tribunals to handle some areas of administrative law.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The actions of executive agencies and independent agencies are the main focus of American administrative law.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] In response to the rapid creation of new independent agencies in the early twentieth century (see discussion below), Congress enacted the Administrative Procedure Act (**APA**) in 1946.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Because the United States Constitution sets no limits on this tripartite authority of administrative agencies, Congress enacted the APA to establish fair administrative law procedures to comply with the constitutional requirements of due process.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Agency procedures are drawn from four sources of authority: the APA, organic statutes, agency rules, and informal agency practice.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Agencies can only act within their congressionally delegated authority, and must comply with the requirements of the APA.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] At the state level, the first version of the Model State Administrative Procedure Act was promulgated and published in 1946 by the Uniform Law Commission (ULC), in which year the Federal Administrative Procedure Act was drafted.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] It incorporates basic principles with only enough elaboration of detail to support essential features, therefore it is a "model", and not a "uniform", act.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] A model act is needed because state administrative law in the states is not uniform, and there are a variety of approaches used in the various states.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The present version is the 2010 Model State Administrative Procedure Act (**MSAPA**) which maintains the continuity with earlier ones.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The reason for the revision is that, in the past two decades state legislatures, dissatisfied with agency rule-making and adjudication, have enacted statutes that modify administrative adjudication and rule-making procedure.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The American Bar Association's official journal concerning administrative law is the *Administrative Law Review*, a quarterly publication that is managed and edited by students at the Washington College of Law.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The agricultural sector is one of the most heavily regulated sectors in the U.S. economy, as it is regulated in various ways at the international, federal, state, and local levels.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] Consequently, administrative law is a significant component of the discipline of agricultural law.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/administrative-law] The United States Department of Agriculture and its myriad agencies such as the Agricultural Marketing Service are the primary sources of regulatory activity, although other administrative bodies such as the Environmental Protection Agency play a significant regulatory role as well.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In the U.S. it has a legal status in itself, whereas in some countries it is legally persuasive without being a legal document.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A living will is one form of advance directive, leaving instructions for treatment.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Another form is a specific type of power of attorney or health care proxy, in which the person authorizes someone (an agent) to make decisions on their behalf when they are incapacitated.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] People are often encouraged to complete both documents to provide comprehensive guidance regarding their care, although they may be combined into a single form.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] An example of combination documents includes the Five Wishes in the United States.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The term *living will* is also the commonly recognised vernacular in many countries, especially the U.K.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The legality of advance consent for advance healthcare directives depends on jurisdiction.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Advance directives were created in response to the increasing sophistication and prevalence of medical technology.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Numerous studies have documented critical deficits in the medical care of the dying; it has been found to be unnecessarily prolonged, painful, expensive, and emotionally burdensome to both patients and their families.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The living will is the oldest form of advance directive.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] It was first proposed by an Illinois attorney, Luis Kutner, in a speech to the Euthanasia Society of America in 1967 and published in a law journal in 1969.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Kutner drew from existing estate law, by which an individual can control property affairs after death (i.e., when no longer available to speak for himself or herself) and devised a way for an individual to express their health care desires when no longer able to express current healthcare wishes.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Because this form of "will" was to be used while an individual was still alive (but no longer able to make decisions), it was dubbed the "living will".
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Patient Self-Determination Act (PSDA) went into effect in December 1991 and required healthcare providers (primarily hospitals, nursing homes, and home health agencies) to give patients information about their rights to make advance directives under state law.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A living will usually provides specific directives about the course of treatment healthcare providers and caregivers are to follow.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In some cases a living will may forbid the use of various kinds of burdensome medical treatment.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] It may also be used to express wishes about the use or foregoing of food and water, if supplied via tubes or other medical devices.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The living will is used only if the individual has become unable to give informed consent or refusal due to incapacity.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A living will can be very specific or very general.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] More specific living wills may include information regarding an individual's desire for such services such as analgesia (pain relief), antibiotics, hydration, feeding, and the use of ventilators or cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] However, studies have also shown that adults are more likely to complete these documents if they are written in everyday language and less focused on technical treatments.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] However, by the late 1980s, public advocacy groups became aware that many people remained unaware of advance directives and even fewer actually completed them.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In part, this was seen as a failure of health care providers and medical organizations to promote and support the use of these documents.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The public's response was to press for further legislative support.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The most recent result was the Patient Self-Determination Act of 1990, which attempted to address this awareness problem by requiring health care institutions to better promote and support the use of advance directives.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Living wills proved to be very popular, and by 2007, 41% of Americans had completed a living will.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In response to public needs, state legislatures soon passed laws in support of living wills in virtually every state in the union.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] However, as living wills began to be better recognized, key deficits were soon discovered.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Most living wills tended to be limited in scope and often failed to fully address presenting problems and needs.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Further, many individuals wrote out their wishes in ways that might conflict with quality medical practice.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Ultimately, it was determined that a living will alone might be insufficient to address many important health care decisions.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Living wills also reflect a moment in time, and may therefore need regular updating to ensure that the correct course of action can be chosen.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Power of attorney statutes have existed in the United States since the days of "common law" (i.e., laws brought from England to the United States during the colonial period).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] These early powers of attorney allowed an individual to name someone to act in their stead.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] People will normally benefit from having both a durable power of attorney and a healthcare proxy.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A healthcare proxy document appoints a person, the proxy, who can make decisions on behalf of the granting individual in the event of incapacity.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The appointed healthcare proxy has, in essence, the same rights to request or refuse treatment that the individual would have if still capable of making and communicating health care decisions.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The appointed representative is authorized to make real-time decisions in actual circumstances, as opposed to advance decisions framed in hypothetical situations, as might be recorded in a living will.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The healthcare proxy was rapidly accepted within the U.S. and authorizing legislation was soon enacted in most states.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] One problem with a conventional healthcare proxy is that it may not be possible for the appointed proxy to determine what care choices the individual would have made if still capable, as healthcare proxies may be too vague for meaningful interpretation.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] While a study comparing next-of-kin decisions on behalf of an incapacitated person, (who later recovered) found that these surrogates chose correctly 68% of the time overall.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Studies suggest that values regarding financial and psychological burden are strong motivators in not wanting a broad array of end-of-life therapies.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Another alternative to a conventional healthcare proxy is the **medical directive**, a document that describes six case scenarios for advance medical decision-making.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The scenarios are each associated with a roster of commonly considered medical procedures and interventions, allowing the individual to decide in advance which treatments are wanted or not wanted under the circumstances.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A study conducted to address concerns that a non-statutory advance directive might leave an incapacitated person with a document that may not be honored found that they are generally accepted.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A PAD can inform others about what treatment they want or do not want from psychiatrists or other mental health professionals, and it can identify a person to whom they have given the authority to make decisions on their behalf.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A mental health advance directive is one kind of advance health care directive.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In the United States, although 25 states have now passed legislation in the past decade establishing authority for PADs, there is relatively little public information available to address growing interest in these legal documents.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The Joint Commission on the Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations (JCAHO) requires behavioral health facilities to ask patients if they have PADs.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] PADs also provide a transportable document—increasingly accessible through electronic directories—to convey information about a detainee's treatment history, including medical disorders, emergency contact information, and medication side effects.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Clinicians often have limited information about citizens detained and labeled as psychiatric patients who present or are coercively presented and labeled as in crisis.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A PAD may help clinicians gain prompt access to relevant information about individual cases and thus improve the quality of clinical decision-making, and enhance patient safety and long-term autonomy.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] National surveys in the United States indicate that although approximately 70% of people targeted by coercive psychiatry laws would want a PAD if offered assistance in completing one, less than 10% have actually completed a PAD.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In a survey conducted of 600 psychiatrists, psychologists, and social workers showed that the vast majority thought advance care planning for crises would help improve patients' overall mental health care.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Further, the more clinicians knew about PAD laws, the more favorable were their attitudes toward these practices.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Many clinicians reported not knowing enough about how PADs work and specifically indicated they lacked resources to readily help patients fill out PADs or to help their clients develop crisis plans.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The laws regarding advance directives, powers of attorney, and enduring guardianships vary from state to state.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In Queensland, for example, the concept of an advance health directive is defined in the *Powers of attorney act of 1998* and *Guardianship and Administration act of 2000*.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Tasmania has no specific legislation concerning advance healthcare directives.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Advance Care Planning (ACP) has been gaining prominence in Australia for its role in enhancing a patient's autonomy and as an important component of good end-of-life care.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Health Canada – Canada's federal health agency – has acknowledged the need for a greater investment in palliative and hospice care as the country faces a rapidly growing population of elderly and terminally ill citizens.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Canada has focused on advance care planning which involves encouraging individuals to reflect on and express their wishes for future care, including end-of-life care, before they become terminally ill or incapable of making decisions for themselves.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In 2008, The Advance Care Planning in Canada: A National Framework and Implementation Project was founded.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The goal was to engage healthcare professionals and educate patients about the importance of advance care planning and end of life care.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Polling indicates that 96% of Canadians think that having a conversation with a loved one about planning for the end of life is important.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] However, the same polls show that only about 13% have actually done so, or have created an advance care plan for themselves.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A 2014 Ipsos Reid Survey reveals that only about a third of Canadian doctors and nurses working in primary care feel comfortable discussing end of life issues with their patients.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] End-of-life issues in Canada have recently been highlighted due to the ongoing related debate about physician-assisted death in Canada.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In the UK, emergency care and treatment plans (e.g.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] ReSPECT) are clinical recommendations written by healthcare professionals after discussion with patients or their relatives about their priorities of care.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Research has found that the involvement of patients or their family in forming ECTP (emergency care and treatment plan) recommendations is variable.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In England and Wales, people may make an advance directive or appoint a proxy under the Mental Capacity Act 2005.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] This is only for an advance refusal of treatment for when the person lacks mental capacity; to be legally binding, the advance decision must be specific about the treatment that is being refused and the circumstances in which the refusal will apply.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] To be valid, the person must have been competent and must have understood the decision when they signed the directive.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Where the patient's advance decision relates to a refusal of life-prolonging treatment this must be recorded in writing and witnessed.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Any advance refusal is legally binding providing that the patient is an adult, the patient was competent and properly informed when reaching the decision, it is clearly applicable to the present circumstances and there is no reason to believe that the patient has changed their mind.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] If an advance decision does not meet these criteria but appears to set out a clear indication of the patient's wishes, it will not be legally binding but should be taken into consideration in determining the patient's best interests.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In June 2010, the Wealth Management Solicitors, Moore Blatch, announced that research showed demand for Living Wills had trebled in the two years previous, indicating the rising level of people concerned about the way in which their terminal illness will be managed.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] According to the British Government, every adult with mental capacity has the right to agree to or refuse medical treatment.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] To make their advance wishes clear, people can use a living will, which can include general statements about wishes, which are not legally binding, and specific refusals of treatment called "advance decisions" or "advance directives".
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] On 18 June 2009 the Bundestag passed a law on advance directives, applicable since 1 September 2009.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Such law, based on the principle of the right of self-determination, provides for the assistance of a fiduciary and of the physician.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] On 14 December 2017, Italian Senate officially approved a law on advance healthcare directive that came into force on 31 January 2018.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Controversy over end-of-life care emerged in Italy in 2006, when a terminally ill patient suffering from muscular dystrophy, Piergiorgio Welby, petitioned the courts for removal of his respirator.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Debated in Parliament, no decision was reached.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A doctor eventually honored Welby's wishes by removing the respirator under sedation.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The physician was initially charged for violating Italy's laws against euthanasia, but was later cleared.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Further debate ensued after the father of a 38-year-old woman, Eluana Englaro, petitioned the courts for permission to withdraw feeding tubes to allow her to die.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Englaro had been in a coma for 17 years, following a car accident.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] After petitioning the courts for 10 years, authorization was granted and Englaro died in February 2009.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In May 2008, apparently as a result of the recent Court of Cassation's holding in the case of Englaro, a guardianship judge in Modena, Italy used relatively new legislation to work around the lack of the advance directive legislation.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The new law permitted a judicially appointed guardian ("amministratore di sostegno") to make decisions for an individual.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Advance healthcare directives are not legally recognized in Japan.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] According to a 2017 survey by the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare (MHLW), 66% of surveyed individuals supported the idea of such directives, but only 8.1% had prepared their own.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The private organization Nihon Songenshi Kyōkai (Japan Society for Dying with Dignity) offers members a semi-standardized "living will" (ribingu uiru) form that is registered with the organization, though it holds no legal weight.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Advance healthcare directives are legally recognized in Korea since 2016, when the Act on Decisions on Life-Sustaining Treatment for Patients in Hospice and Palliative Care was implemented in Korea, providing a broad framework for end-of-life decision-making.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Advance healthcare directives is yet to be legalised in Nigeria, and patient’s “written directives” for determining their preferences, tradition still dominates in Nigeria and most African countries.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In 2005, the Knesset passed a law allowing people to write advance care directives.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Right to refuse care is only recognized if the patient is considered terminally ill and their life expectancy is less than six months.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In Switzerland, there are several organizations which take care of registering patient decrees, forms which are signed by the patients declaring that in case of permanent loss of judgement (e.g., inability to communicate or severe brain damage) all means of prolonging life shall be stopped.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Family members and these organizations also keep proxies which entitle their holder to enforce such patient decrees.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Establishing such decrees is relatively uncomplicated.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In 2013 a law concerning advance healthcare directives has been voted.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Every adult with testamentary capacity can redact a legal binding document declaring a will in the event of loss of judgement.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] They may also designate a natural person to discuss medical procedures with the attending doctor and make decisions on their behalf if they are longer capable of judgment.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Aggressive medical intervention leaves nearly two million Americans confined to nursing homes, and over 1.4 million Americans remain so medically frail as to survive only through the use of feeding tubes.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Of U.S. deaths, about a third occur in health care facilities.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] As many as 30,000 persons are kept alive in comatose and permanently vegetative states.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Cost burdens to individuals and families are considerable.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] A national study found that: "In 20% of cases, a family member had to quit work", 31% lost "all or most savings" (even though 96% had insurance), and "20% reported loss of [their] major source of income".
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Yet, studies indicate that 70-95% of people would rather refuse aggressive medical treatment than have their lives medically prolonged in incompetent or other poor prognosis states.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The first formal response was the living will.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In the United States, all states recognize some form of living wills or the designation of a health care proxy.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The term *living will* is not officially recognized under California law, but an advance health care directive or durable power of attorney may be used for the same purpose as a living will.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] In Pennsylvania on November 30, 2006, Governor Edward Rendell signed into law Act 169, that provides a comprehensive statutory framework governing advance health care directives and health care decision-making for incompetent patients.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Several states offer living will "registries" where citizens can file their living will so that they are more easily and readily accessible by doctors and other health care providers.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] However, in recent years some of these registries, such as the one run by the Washington State Department of Health, have been shuttered by the state government because of low enrollment, lack of funds, or both.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] On July 28, 2009, Barack Obama became the first United States President to announce publicly that he had a living will, and to encourage others to do the same.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] He told an AARP town meeting, "So I actually think it's a good idea to have a living will.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Shortly afterwards, bioethicist Jacob Appel issued a call to make living wills mandatory.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] Supreme Court of India on March 9, 2018, permitted living wills and withholding and withdrawing life sustaining treatments.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/advance-healthcare-directive] The country's apex court held that the right to a dignified life extends up to the point of having a dignified death.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] In law, **incorporation by reference** is the act of including a second document within another document by only mentioning the second document.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] This act, if completed properly, makes the entire second document a part of the main document.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] Incorporation by reference is often found in laws, regulations, contracts, legal and regulated documentation.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] In American administrative law, incorporation by reference is a drafting tool that enables federal agencies to give legal effect to materials that are already published elsewhere.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] This is allowed under a provision of the Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(1).
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] Section 552(a) requires agencies to publish regulations in the Federal Register in order to enforce them.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] Section 552(a)(1) provides that if material published elsewhere is "reasonably available to the class of persons affected" and the Director of the Federal Register approves its incorporation by reference, that material will be "deemed published" in the Federal Register.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] It is most controversially used to incorporate privately authored voluntary consensus standards into health and safety regulations without infringing the standards developers' copyright.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] Federal law and policy, embodied in the National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act of 1995 and Office of Management and Budget (OMB) Circular A-119, requires federal agencies to use these standards instead of creating "government-unique" technical standards purely to serve regulatory purposes.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] Commercial contracts may refer to separate documents which are incorporated into the primary contract by reference to them.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] Examples include documents containing standard terms and conditions, or references to previous contracts between the two parties, whose terms are to apply to a further transaction.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] In some countries, a specification of a patent application may incorporate by reference the content of a previous patent, patent application, or non-patent publication.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] The information incorporated by reference is treated as part of the text of the application as filed.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] In law regarding wills, it is a doctrine at common law which allows a testator, or a creator of a will, to dispose of assets in his estate in accordance with a separate document.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] 3. the will must clearly manifest the intent that the document be incorporated.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] An exception to the first requirement is made for small gifts of tangible personal property, such as household furniture and items of sentimental value.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] Oral instructions cannot be subject to incorporation by reference.
[src:incorporation-by-reference/incorporation-by-reference] For example, if a testator states in the will that he has recited to a third party the intended disposition of testamentary assets, such attempt to circumvent the requirements of a written will is void.
